message.content:
The standard gauge for railways is a standardized width of 1,435 mm (or 5 feet and 3.5 inches) between the inner faces of the two steel rails, which was set by the London and Birmingham Railway in England in the 1830s. It is commonly used around the world as the most common railroad track width and is known as the International Standard Gauge (ISG). The standard gauge was adopted by other railway companies to ensure compatibility between different lines, which made it easier for trains to travel on different tracks. This standardized width provides a more efficient and sa                   
smoother ride for railroad cars and enables them to carry heavier loads.
